!TITLE
THE OEDIPUS COMPLEX
!WORDS
Sophocles in his Greek classic Oedipus Rex dropped a tantalizing 
riddle on the men of Thebes. “Solve it,” he said, “and you win the 
hand of the widowed Queen of Thebes.” The riddle went like this: What 
is it that walks on four legs at sunrise, on two legs at high noon, 
and on three legs at sunset? Many tried to guess. Only Oedipus came 
up with the right answer: man. He was right. As a baby, he crawls on 
all fours. As an adult, he walks on two legs. In old age, he uses a 
cane and looks three-legged. 

The reward was marriage to the Queen who happened to be Oedipus’ 
mother! He had been discarded as a child, an apparent pretender to 
the throne. From the incident of a son marrying his mother, the term 
“Oedipus complex” became a permanent part of our language.
!TOPICS
OEDIPUS COMPLEX, THE
LANGUAGE
RIDDLES
SOPHOCLES
