!TITLE
ANAPATIST PRINTER THOMAS VON IMBROEK LOST HIS HEAD
!WORDS
Anabaptist printer Thomas von Imbroek Lost His Head
 
THOMAS VON IMBROEK was a printer at Cologne on the Rhine. He was also 
an Anabaptist—not of the revolutionary kind, such as John of Leiden 
had been, but a man of a peaceable, Christian spirit. He founded 
congregations of believers outside of the established church and 
wrote a confession of faith for them. 

His failure to baptize his children, however, seems to be what 
brought him to the attention of authorities. After his arrest, a pair 
of priests questioned him closely on his rejection of infant baptism. 
When he insisted that only believers should be baptized, they 
pronounced him a heretic. He was brought to the rack, but was not 
tortured on it since the city’s magistrates disagreed on how to deal 
with him. Days passed in which he was cruelly tortured by other means 
and pressured to convert to Catholicism.
 
Eventually he was taken to a landgrave’s house (a noble equivalent to 
a count.) The landgrave would have released Imbroek had he not feared 
reprisal from the German emperor and the bishop. Therefore, Imbroek 
was eventually condemned to death as a heretic in his presence. 

Meanwhile, his wife wrote him letters, encouraging him to stand firm. 
In reply, he assured her that the Lord “refreshes the afflicted souls 
that thirst for Him. He is a shadow from the heat of the sun,” and 
quoted from Matthew and Isaiah to back up his hope. 

He added, “Tell the brethren to take care of the novices (young 
believers) and to pray earnestly for me. I will also pray for them, 
as much as is in my power. Remember my bonds. The Lord be with your 
spirit. Amen.” 

To his persecutors he offered this speech: 

“I am willing and ready, both to live or to die. I do not care what 
happens to me. God will not let me down. I am comforted and in good 
spirits while yet on the earth. God gives me friendly assurance, and 
my heart is encouraged through my brothers. Sword, water, 
fire...cannot frighten me...All the persecution in this world shall 
not be able to separate me from God.” 

Imbroek was just twenty-five when an executioner lopped off his head 
on this day, 5 March 1558.
—Dan Graves
!TOPICS
ANABAPTIST PRINTER LOST HIS HEAD
MARTYRS
PERSECUTION BY CHRISTIANS
!BASE=FRS-4/9999
!SOURCE=3
!MSTATUS=3
!TCAID=0
!END


!TITLE
HONESTY IS A PROBLEM FOR LOTS OF PEOPLE, INCLUDING PREACHERS
!WORDS
            I was at the Southern Baptist Convention in Houston, 
Texas in 1979. Up to that time, Southern Baptists have largely been a 
moderate people who were willing for others to hold their own view. 
That was getting ready to change. “Fundamentalist” is a word for 
people who believe in a literal, inerrant interpretation of 
scripture. In an effort to pad the vote for one of these people to 
become president, it happened to be a pastor in this case, some who 
were not elected messengers from their churches registered as though 
they were. That’s grossly dishonest and a violation of their 
constitution

             One Virginian registered and voted who wasn’t a member 
of any SBC church. Children’s ballots were given to other adults for 
more “judicious” use. One must be present to vote, but in the final 
tally, there were more votes cast than there were people present for 
the election. I might add that the huge majority of voters were 
Baptist pastors, their staff or their family members. What are we 
talking about here?  Honesty, plain and simple and character or in 
this case the lack of it. I learned that day that Southern Baptists 
would lie as quickly as anybody else if it was necessary to win. It 
was the darkest day in the history of Souhern Baptists, but they 
wanted to win, and they did.
