!TITLE
EVALUATION OF A CLASS TAUGHT BY FRED R. SKAGGS
!WORDS

                                                                                      
November 19, 1973
                         
Academy of Parish Clergy, Inc.
3100 W. Lake Street
Minneapolis, Minnesota 55416
         
Gentlemen:
         
           As requested, I enthusiastically report on the class 
offered by the University
of Richmond in its off—campus School of Christian Studies, for the 
fall semester 1972
entitled, “The Christian Family” which was taught by Dr. Fred Skaggs. 
While the descrip-
tion of the subject matter looked interesting and challenging, the 
class itself turned out to
be extremely helpful and gave me new hope for logical areas in which 
the church could
witness effectively.
         
          A schedule of assignments for the semester from a variety 
of books including
some text books for the course was given me on the first evening I 
attended. Text books
were not limited to any particular church press and were generally 
paperback editions.
The variety of material was refreshing and even though the same 
general matter might be
touched on in two books, the approach and treatment were different. 
Assignments were
made for each individual to present the material for an evening. This 
approach stimulated
better assignment of responsibility, encouraged discussion, provoked 
fuller participation.
Dr. Skaggs led but did not dominate the discussion yet kept the 
remarks on the subject.
Included in the class were two ladies in their forties, two young 
ladies in their late teens or
maybe 20 and myself, 55 years old. He used the variety of attitudes 
represented by this
diverse group to bring out in extremely frank, provocative and 
helpful discussion. Facts
could be examined and conclusions revealed without embarrassment 
under his careful
direction. The course presented the Christian view of the family, 
love, courtship, sex
relationships, the problems of old age, etc. All were presented in 
the bright clear light of
biblical criticism and we saw what principles lay behind Christian 
positions. From the      
course, those who attended were able to deal more adequately with 
leading others to
accept Christian principles rather than lean on the insecure 
admonition, “nice girls don’t 
do things like that.”
         
         Dr. Skaggs’ direction of the class period assured that the 
time was well spent in
learning. Currently, I serve as Manager of Supply and Distribution 
for Mobil Chemical Company,
and was an officer in the Navy in World War II. I have been exposed 
to college classroom
teaching, corporate instruction and at least ten separate Bible 
classes at the University of 
Richmond. Without hesitation I believe manner of presentation and 
subject matter itself to 
have been a real help to me in my relationship within my own family 
and gives me a wider 
understanding of what position the church must take today to 
effectively survive this 
so called “new morality” era.
         
        An assignment for an outside paper was made whereby each 
person was assigned
a denomination to investigate to determine what publications, 
periodicals, films, pamphlets,
etc. have been produced by that denomination and to critique these 
for the benefit of the
class. This study had to be accomplished as an independent effort. In 
addition to the
individual’s enlightenment, the sum of the efforts of all was 
significant.
         
       Dr. Skaggs is a learned man, skilled in teaching and 
stimulating others about
him to learn. Certainly his direction and teaching of this class 
identifies him as an
outstanding scholar in the Christian field of education and conduct.
         
                                             Very truly yours,
         
                                            
                                             R.  R. Martin
         
         bh	
