!TITLE
RECONCILING DIFFERENCES BETWEEN GOSPEL OF MARK AND JOHN
!WORDS
  Reconciling Differences between Two Canonical Gospels

          Scholars have come to believe that some of the stories of 
Jesus’ life in the New Testament Gospels contain discrepancies 
between each other. Consider, for example, the Gospels of Mark and 
John.

          The Gospels of Mark and John both give readers an account 
of when Jesus was crucified in relation to the Last Supper— though 
the nature of this meal differs. Mark specifically refers to the 
event as the Passover meal, while John does not.
                 
Both Mark and John give us a precise description of when, in 
relationship to the Passover meal, Jesus was crucified.
         
Both Mark and John indicate that Jesus died during the Feast of the 
Passover, the annual festival celebrated by Jews in Jerusalem to 
commemorate the events of the  Exodus. The festival had as its 
background the stories of God’s deliverance of his people Israel from 
their slavery in Egypt, through Moses, as recorded in the book of 
Exodus in the Hebrew Bible. In Jesus’ day, the festival was a major 
event. Jews         came from around the world to celebrate the feast 
in Jerusalem. They would arrive a week in advance to undergo a ritual 
of purification that would allow them to eat the meal. They needed to 
be ritually pure for a week, and so they’d come a week early.

The afternoon before the Passover meal was eaten, Jews would bring a 
lamb, which was to be eaten as part of the celebration, to the 
temple, or else they would purchase a lamb there at the temple so 
that it could be sacrificed by the priests. The rest of the day was 
spent in preparing the meal for that evening. That day, when they 
prepared the meal, therefore, was called the “day of preparation for 
the Passover.” Now, it’s important to remember that in Jewish 
reckoning, a new day begins not at midnight as it does for us, but 
when it gets dark. Even today, Jewish Sabbath begins on Friday 
evening at dark and continues through Saturday until it gets dark 
again.
         
During the festival, after the lambs were sacrificed, their blood 
drained, they were given back to the Jewish worshipers, who took them 
home to cook them for the meal, which was then eaten after it got 
dark—that is, on the day of Passover itself. The meal itself 
consisted of several symbolic foods to recall Israel’s slavery in 
Egypt and deliverance by God.
         
         Mark on the Last Supper

         Now we’re ready to compare in detail two Gospel accounts of 
Jesus’ arrest and trial. The comparison is interesting, because both 
Mark and John give us a precise description of when, in relationship 
to the Passover meal, Jesus was crucified. Let’s         begin with 
the earlier account, the account of Mark.

         The day before his arrest, in the Gospel of Mark, Jesus’ 
disciples ask him where they are to prepare, for themselves and 
Jesus, the Passover meal (Mark chapter 14, verse 12). Jesus gives 
them instructions. This, then, is taking place on the day of 
preparation for the Passover. They prepare the meal. That night, they 
have it. At the meal, Jesus takes the symbolic foods of the Passover 
and instills new significance in them. He takes the bread and says, 
“This is my body.” He takes the cup of wine         and says, “This 
is the cup of the new covenant in my blood.” Afterward, according to 
Mark, Jesus goes out to pray. He’s betrayed by Judas Iscariot, handed 
over to Jewish authorities for trial, and spends the night in jail.

         The next morning, that is, the morning of Passover, the day 
after the lambs were slain, the morning after the Passover meal had 
been eaten, Jesus appears before the Roman governor Pontius Pilate, 
who finds him guilty of criminal charges and orders         him 
executed. Jesus is immediately taken off and is crucified.  According 
to Mark chapter 15, verse 25, it takes place at 9:00 in the morning. 
And so Jesus is executed at 9:00 in the morning the day of the 
Passover, the day after the lambs have been killed         and eaten.
         
         John’s Version of Events

         This dating of the event in Mark stands in stark contrast 
with what we find in the Gospel of John. Here, too, Jesus has a last 
meal with his disciples, but in John there’s no word of it being a 
Passover meal. The disciples in this Gospel never ask Jesus         
where they are to prepare the Passover for him, and Jesus does not 
speak about the symbolic foods in a new way at this meal. He has a 
last meal, but there’s no word about it being a Passover meal.

           After the meal, again, he goes out to pray. He’s betrayed 
by Judas. He’s arrested. He spends the night in jail, and the next 
day he appears before Pontius Pilate. We’re told that the Jewish 
leaders who are his accusers refuse to enter Pilate’s residence 
because they don’t want to become ritually defiled and so prevented 
from eating the Passover meal that evening:  chapter 18, verse 28. 
Eat the Passover meal that evening? Hadn’t they already eaten the 
meal the night before?

          The problem is clarified at the end of Jesus’s trial, when 
we’re told exactly when he was condemned and led off to be executed: 
John chapter 19, verse 14. Pilate pronounces his condemnation of 
Jesus, and we’re told now that it was the day of preparation for the 
Passover. It was about noon. The day of preparation for the Passover? 
How could it be the day of preparation? According to Mark’s Gospel, 
Jesus lived through that day, had the Passover meal with his 
disciples that evening, and was put on the cross the next morning, on 
the day of Passover itself. In John’s Gospel, though, Jesus was 
executed before the meal even began.

          It’s probably impossible to reconcile this discrepancy if 
you want to explain how both accounts can be historically accurate. 
Jesus is killed at a different time, on a differ-         ent day, in 
John than in the Synoptics. It is possible to explain, however, why 
the discrepancy came about.      

                         Making Jesus “the Lamb of God”

         The Gospel of John is the only Gospel of the New Testament 
that explicitly identifies Jesus himself as “the Lamb of God who 
takes away the sins of the world.”         These are the words of 
John the Baptist, in John chapter 1, verse 29. He says the same thing 
seven verses later: “Behold the Lamb of God.” This is also the only 
Gospel         in which Jesus is said to die on the afternoon of the 
day before the Passover, precisely when the lambs were being 
slaughtered.
         
          In the judgment of most scholars, it appears that John has 
changed a historical datum in order to make a theological point. That 
is to say that he’s changed the day and the hour of Jesus’s death 
precisely to show that Jesus really was the Lamb of God, who was 
slain on the same day and at the same hour and at the hands of the 
same people—the chief priests, who slew the Passover lambs.

          This is one kind of evidence to suggest that the Gospels 
contain some accounts that cannot be historically accurate, at least 
in all their details, because John and Mark can’t be reconciled on 
these terms, even though you can explain why you have the         
discrepancy.
!TOPICS
SYNOPTIC ISSUES IN MARK AND JOHN
MARK AND JOHN, GOSPEL DIFFERENCES
!SCRIPTURES
MARK 
JOHN
