!TITLE
EUTHYMIUS BEHEADED FOR HIS FAITH
!WORDS
March 22, 1814

Saint Euthymius was killed about noon on March 22, 1814 in 
Constantinople, thereby earning a place in the heavenly Kingdom where 
he glorifies the holy, consubstantial, and life-creating Trinity, the 
Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit, forevermore. The head of Saint 
Euthymius is in the Monastery of Saint Panteleimon on Mt. Athos.

He had abandoned Christianity for Islam in his youth but soon 
regretted it, returned to faith, became a monk on Mt. Athos, and 
practiced great austerities. Eventually he traveled to Constantinople 
where he testified of his faith.
