!TITLE
ONOMATOPEI
!WORDS
Onomatopoei

The word "hiss" is an example of an onomatopoeia. Onomatopoeia is the 
use of words that imitate the sounds associated with the objects or 
actions they refer to (such as hiss or murmur ). It can also include 
made-up words or simply a series of letters, such as zzzzzz to 
represent a person sleeping or snoring.

Onomatopoeia is often used by poets because it allows the reader to 
visualize the scene by creating a multi-sensory experience, all with 
words. Readers don't just picture the scene, they hear the sounds in 
nature or feel the chill in the air — as these examples, from the 
classics to modern verse poems with onomatopoeia, demonstrate.

Common onomatopoeias include animal noises such as oink, meow (or 
miaow), roar, and chirp. Onomatopoeia can differ between languages: 
it conforms to some extent to the broader linguistic system.
!TOPICS
ONOMATOPEI
LANGUAGE
WORDS THAT SOUND LIKE
