!TITLE
THE THREE PRIMACIES IN CHRISTIAN HISTORY
!WORDS
Sherrill G. Stevens  4/15/23

 I have learned in studying the biblical text that three "primacies" 
have developed in Christian history.  Primacy = preeminence.  Only 
one of the three has been "named" a primacy in the definitions of 
Christian theology and ecclesiology.  The three are "the primacy of 
Peter," "the primacy of Paul," and "the primacy of Jesus."  I have 
found that a basic understanding of these three theological and 
practical streams has been helpful to me as I have tried to relate 
biblical writings and church practices.  

(4/17) The primacy of Peter.  This is the "doctrine of preeminence" 
which has had historic naming and definition.  This tenet that Peter 
was the preeminent disciple/apostle was based on (1) the statement by 
Jesus in Matthew 16:18-19, "... on this rock I will build my church 
(and) I will give you the keys of the kingdom ... ;  (2) the 
commission by Jesus in John 21:16-17, "... feed my lambs, ... tend my 
sheep, ... feed my sheep..." ;  and (3) the "front-upsman-ship" of 
Peter throughout their time with Jesus and in the first five chapters 
of Acts.  During the first decades of the Christian movement, the 
Twelve Apostles were "accepted" as "most important" because of their 
personal association with Jesus.  Paul claimed "equality" with them.  
By AD 150, "church leaders" began to claim "clerical privileges" for 
themselves (that nobody else had "authority" to "administer" the 
rituals of baptism and the "Supper").  By AD 200 a hierarchy of 
clergy developed: bishops were first, then metropolitan bishops 
became superior to local priests in the area.  Early on, the bishop 
of Rome gained recognition as the "most important bishop" because he 
was bishop in the "capitol city" and had the support of the emperor.  
A "church father" Irenaeus (lived AD 132-202) wrote about Peter as 
the first bishop of Rome.  By AD 500, Gregory the Great, as bishop of 
Rome had "solidified" the claim of "that office" as superior above 
all the bishops of the universal church.  The Roman Catholic papacy 
had become established.  There were always dissenter movements which 
remained out of the Roman hierarchical orbit.  The Roman Catholic 
clergy hierarchy led in the development of a clergy-controlled 
church, with sacraments retained in their sole administration --- 
using the "primacy of Peter" as their basic authority.  In AD 1868, 
the First Vatican Council declared that "The Primacy of the Bishop of 
Rome over the whole Catholic Church is an essential and eternal 
institution."  That's one "stream" of Christian religious belief and 
practice.

The primacy of Paul.  This has never (before) been stated as a tenet 
of faith (not that I know of).  But here goes.  As the Christian 
movement began to develop, opposition by Jews led to open persecution 
of Christians, and Saul was zealous persecuter until his own 
conversion.  After his conversion Saul/Paul became the best known 
missionary to spread the Christian message, and a chief influence in 
Christianity becoming largely a Gentile religion. We know primarily 
about Paul because of his letters.  Christianity was also being 
spread by other Christians but their missionary work was not widely 
known because it did not become a part of the records in the Bible.  

Now some history.  Paul's letters were the first documents 
"treasured" by churches, copied and circulated as a group in the 
Mediterranean area west of Jerusalem.  His preaching and writing were 
prominent AD 45-65, a generation earlier than the four Gospels were 
written.  One tenet of faith, developed by Paul, and written in 
detail in Romans 3-5, has prevailed in non-Catholic Christianity 
through the centuries.  It is Paul's "doctrine of salvation."  Paul's 
belief was rooted in two Hebrew sources.  One was the Garden of Eden 
story of human disobedience. The first eleven chapters of Genesis 
were not a part of Hebrew/Israelite religious tradition until about 
500 BC when the oral traditions were put into writing and the first 
eleven chapters of pre-Hebrew stories (from an unknown original 
source) were placed as an introduction. 

The story of Eden is not a record of history.  It is a parable about 
human disobedience and what that disobedience does to human 
relationship with God.  I have not been able to find any references 
to Adam's disobedience as "original sin corrupting all mankind" until 
the apocryphal writings of the inter-testamental period. There is no 
New Testament record about that belief earlier than Paul. 

The second source for Paul's "salvation faith" was "substitute 
sacrifice."  After the Israelite Exodus from Egypt, Moses declared 
that God had claimed ownership of all firstborn of man or beast 
because God had spared all Israelite firstborn when all Egyptian 
firstborn had been killed in the death plague (Ex. 13:1,11-16).  All 
firstborn must be sacrificed to God or destroyed.  But the principle 
of substitution was established.  Sons could not be sacrificed so a 
lamb was to be sacrificed instead.  A less valuable animal (lamb) 
could be sacrificed as substitute for a more valuable animal 
(donkey). The principle of substitute sacrifice became the basis for 
the Mosaic law of animal blood sacrifice as atonement for human sin.  
Paul took "original sin" and "substitute blood sacrifice" and made of 
them the tenet of faith that God had an eternal plan from before the 
foundation of the world to put forth Jesus as a substitute sacrifice 
through crucifixion to atone for the original sin of Adam which had 
passed onto all humanity, and offer salvation by grace to all who 
would have faith in that grace gift.  Paul's doctrine of salvation as 
a transactional act of God for forgiveness and eternal salvation has 
caused Paul to have become and been the primary theological "father" 
of non-Catholic Christianity. Hence, the primacy of Paul to a major 
stream of Christian faith.

The primacy of Jesus. The man Jesus was Jewish, so defined by having 
been born of a Jewish mother.  He was "dedicated" (Jewish fashion) at 
birth, which means that he was circumcised (considered an essential 
mark if identity in Jewish culture and religion).  It can readily be 
assumed that he practiced Mosaic ritual religion throughout life up 
until his entry into public ministry at age 30. 

Jesus was baptized by John the Baptist and spent time alone in the 
Judean wilderness making decision about how he would "do ministry" 
among people.  From that point on he "turned Jewish religion upside 
down."  He sometimes attended synagogue and sometimes taught in the 
Temple area, but he apparently did not practice religious rituals 
according to the Mosaic regulations.  He preached that God is 
sovereign (the kingdom is at hand), and people need to repent and 
believe the gospel (Mk. 1:15, Mt. 4:17). 

Jesus called on people to believe in God and in himself, to have 
faith in the good news about God and life that he was teaching, to 
change their mind and way of life (repent), and to trust God to give 
"new birth" (transformation of life) and ever-present help for living 
in harmony with God.  Jesus did not teach, practice, nor reveal that 
any ritual was required to receive forgiveness and a right 
relationship with God.  Jesus was so violently opposed by the Jewish 
hierarchal priesthood that they secured his execution by Roman 
authority, hoping to eliminate his teaching and influence. 

His followers became convinced of his resurrection from death.  They 
began a movement of "followers of the way," and Christianity was 
born.  I have written in two previous posts about the way two 
"streams of Christian faith" have developed which believe and 
practice different tenets of faith about the way people are "made 
right" with God and live out a Christian life. Those streams have 
developed around "the primacy of Peter," and "the primacy of Paul."  
There has always been a third stream, based on belief that Jesus is 
the preeminent religious authority as personal self-revelation by 
God, and that salvation is received through repentant faith and 
spiritual new birth.  This stream of Christian faith and practice is 
based on "the primacy of Jesus."
