!TITLE
THE LEGACY OF HATRED
!WORDS
Yom HaShoah, whether it’s a Jewish time or a Gentile time, is a 
perfect time to set aside a little spiritual energy for the purpose 
of pondering how the legacy of hatred that culminated in the 
Holocaust happened and if it can happen again, and where. 

	What is it that allows a German soldier, possibly a family man 
himself, to take a baby or a young child and crack its spine over his 
knees like kindling wood?  Or to smash a child’s skull against a wall 
just to hear it pop?  Or throw little children into the fire alive, 
not wanting to waste a bullet? What is it that will do that to a 
person?    
                       
	 What is it that allows a medical doctor, sworn by his Hippocratic 
oath to do good and not harm, when he is notified by the Berlin 
Anthropological Museum  that it needs some skeletons for use in the 
museum, to reach over into the crowd of prisoners and get a father 
and son, have them killed and cooked so that the flesh could more 
quickly be stripped from their bones and the skeletons shipped faster 
to the museum? What is that? The infamous Dr. Mengele did that at 
Auschwitz.  

	What is it that allows a medical doctor to place subjects under 
water and dissect them while they are alive to see if this would 
demonstrate air embolism in the blood vessels of the heart and 
brain?  Dr. Sigmund Rascher did that at Dachau. Why?

--------------------------------

	Many of the Christian Crusaders to go to the Holy Land during the 
First Crusade (1096-1099) viciously plundered and killed many of the 
Jews of Europe to finance their trip.  Once is Jerusalem, they burned 
Jews alive in the chief synagogue, circling the screaming, 
flame-tortured humanity singing “Christ We Adore Thee” with their 
crusader crosses held high. It sounds like a Ku Klux Klan meeting, 
doesn’t it?
 
	In every generation of Christian history, we have written evidence 
of that kind of attitude, and the hatred was building.  Martin 
Luther, a major figure in challenging the Roman Church to clean up 
its act and a gargantuan mover to change church history, was also a 
major violator of the truth at this point.  He called the Jews 
“venomous,” “bitter worms,” and “disgusting vermin,” the same words 
that Hitler was to use 400 years later. He harassed the local 
government for not using their military power to dispose of the Jews.
!TOPICS
HATRED, THE LEGACY OF
HOLOCAUST
HATRED
MARTIN LUTHER
CRUSADES TO THE HOLY LAND
