!MSTATUS=1
!TCAID=0
!END


!TITLE
I NEVER WENT BACK TO SEE
!WORDS
In a delightful sermon titled, "When the Angels Were Gone," G. L. 
Chappell emphasized that when the angels announced the good news to 
the shepherds, they went to Bethlehem to see the Christ-child for 
themselves.

But then Chappell sets up a hypothetical situation in which the 
shepherds respond quite differently. They see and hear these amazing 
displays. Then they sit around the fire discussing the brightness of 
the angelic appearance and the wonder of the message they heard. But 
they don’t actually go to Bethlehem; they just talk about it.

Years later, in this creative sermon, one of the shepherds tells his 
little grandson about that eventful night. The youngster asks, 
"Granddaddy, was what the angels said really true?" The shepherd 
continues telling him what he had heard about Jesus, even the reports 
of His resurrection. But when the lad keeps asking, “Was what the 
angels said really true?”, all the elderly shepherd could do is shake 
his head and say, "I don't really know, son. I never went to see."
!TOPICS
I NEVER WENT BACK TO SEE
BETHLEHEM
ADVENT
SHEPHERDS AT BETHLEHEM
!SCRIPTURES
