!TITLE
THE SIX WIVES OF HENRY VIII
!WORDS
Henry VIII left an indelible mark on British history, though he is 
remembered as much for his insatiable appetite for women and food as 
for his shrewd political maneuvers. Born in 1491, Henry ascended the 
throne at the young age of 17, succeeding his father, Henry VII. His 
youth was marked by interests in the arts, sports, and education, 
making him the embodiment of a Renaissance man, as well as a 
promising and charismatic ruler. It was the monarch’s matrimonial 
escapades, however, that came to define his legacy. Henry’s reign, 
spanning from 1509 to 1547, was characterized by a series of 
tumultuous marriages entwined in Tudor politics. You may be familiar 
with the old rhyme, “Divorced, beheaded, died, divorced, beheaded, 
survived,” but here’s a closer look at the six women who became the 
wives of Henry VIII.

Catherine of Aragon (queen consort: 1509-1533) 

Henry VIII had been on the throne for only a few weeks when he 
married Catherine of Aragon. The daughter of Spanish rulers Ferdinand 
and Isabella, Catherine was six years older than Henry and was seen 
as a good match for the young monarch. Beautiful, well educated, and 
devoted to Henry, Catherine was also the king’s sister-in-law, having 
married his older brother Arthur in 1501, only to be widowed five 
months later at the age of 16. Her marriage to Henry lasted 24 years, 
but ended in divorce.By all accounts, Henry had loved Catherine, but 
when she failed to give him a male heir, he asked Pope Clement VII to 
declare their marriage invalid, asserting that her marriage to Arthur 
made their union illegitimate in the eyes of God. When the pope 
refused, Henry divorced Catherine so he could marry his pregnant 
mistress (and Catherine’s lady-in-waiting), the French-educated Anne 
Boleyn, setting in motion his break from the Catholic Church and the 
establishment of the Church of England. Despite being divorced, 
dismissed from court, and kept from her only living child, Mary, 
Catherine’s devotion to Henry lasted until her death by cancer in 
1536. The last line of the last letter she wrote him read, “Lastly, I 
make this vow, that mine eyes desire you above all things.”

Anne Boleyn (queen consort: 1533-1536)

Remembered as “Anne of a Thousand Days,” Anne Boleyn is perhaps the 
most famous of Henry’s wives, in part because of the grisly end she 
met just three short years after marrying the king. Anne gave birth 
to Henry’s second daughter, Elizabeth, just three months after she 
was crowned queen consort, and because Mary, Henry’s daughter with 
Katherine, had been declared illegitimate following their divorce, 
Elizabeth was named the heir to the throne. (She was crowned Queen 
Elizabeth I in 1559, and became one of the most famous monarchs in 
English history.)After Anne suffered a series of miscarriages, 
including the stillborn birth of the son Henry so desperately wanted, 
Henry turned his attention to one of Anne’s ladies-in-waiting, Jane 
Seymour. Meanwhile, the king’s adviser Thomas Cromwell, who had once 
been an ally of Anne’s, built a case against her, accusing her of 
numerous crimes including adultery, treason, witchcraft, and incest. 
With little evidence presented to support any of her so-called 
crimes, Anne was nonetheless beheaded at the Tower of London in May 
1536.

Jane Seymour (queen consort: 1536-1537) 

Having served as a lady-in-waiting to both Catherine of Aragon and 
Anne Boleyn, Jane Seymour was well aware of Henry’s desire for a male 
heir. Her virtuous nature caught the Tudor king’s interest and, when 
she rejected a letter and purse of money from Henry on the grounds 
that her honor was more important than riches, he became even more 
besotted. Just days after Anne Boleyn’s death, the newly single Henry 
married Jane, making her his third wife. Jane went on to do what 
Henry’s two previous wives had not: She bore him a living son. Her 
pregnancy was announced in March 1537 and Henry vowed to stay close 
to his wife. She gave birth to their son, Edward, on October 12, only 
to die 12 days later. Their marriage lasted just 17 months, but Jane 
was Henry’s only wife to die as queen and receive a royal funeral. At 
his death, Henry was buried near her in St. George’s Chapel at 
Windsor Castle.

Anne of Cleves (queen consort: 1540) 

Having lost Jane to complications from childbirth, Henry sought to 
form a political alliance with William, Duke of Cleves, the ruler of 
a Protestant territory in Germany, by marrying one of his sisters. 
Henry’s political motivations were only part of his reason for 
deciding to wed again — he also wanted a second son. He chose Anne of 
Cleves as his bride-to-be based on her portrait, and was bitterly 
disappointed by his betrothed’s appearance when they finally met, 
saying, “I see nothing in this woman as men report of her.”Henry was 
no longer interested in marrying plain, innocent Anne, but there was 
no way to back out of the wedding, despite Thomas Cromwell’s 
attempts. Wanting to be free of his betrothed, Henry blamed her 
physical appearance on his inability to consummate their marriage and 
had their union annulled just six months later. Anne and Henry 
maintained an affectionate bond, however, and Anne outlived Henry and 
all of his other wives.

Catherine Howard (queen consort: 1540-1542) 

Having served as a lady-in-waiting to Anne of Cleves, Catherine 
Howard was likely still a teenager when she caught Henry’s eye — but 
she was also far more experienced than her predecessor. Historians 
theorize that Catherine might have been sexually abused by her music 
teacher when she was a young teen, and she had relationships with 
both her grandmother’s secretary and one of Henry’s courtiers before 
marrying the aging monarch just a few weeks after his marriage to 
Anne of Cleves was annulled. Henry seemed happy with his young new 
bride, but when the truth about Catherine’s past relationships came 
to light, as well as accusations of an affair with Thomas Culpeper, a 
friend of the king’s, Henry had her stripped of her title and 
imprisoned. A few months later, she was beheaded for treason and 
adultery. 

Catherine Parr (queen consort: 1543-1547) 

Henry VIII’s last wife was Catherine Parr, a widow and scholar known 
as the “lucky queen,” as she survived the death of the fickle king. 
Married and widowed twice, Catherine met Henry while serving as a 
lady-in-waiting to his eldest daughter, Mary Tudor. Catherine’s 
mother, Maud, had been a lady-in-waiting for Catherine of Aragon, and 
Maud named her daughter in honor of Henry’s first wife. Catherine 
Parr resisted Henry’s marriage appeals at first, in part because she 
was in love with someone else in the king’s circle: Thomas Seymour, 
the brother of Henry’s third wife, Jane, and uncle to his son Edward. 
But Henry was not deterred, and he married Catherine in 1543 at age 
52. After their marriage, Catherine proved to be a unifying force as 
stepmother to Henry’s three children. A religious reformer and the 
first woman in England to publish a book in her own name, Catherine 
was widowed for a third time when Henry died on January 28, 1547. The 
king’s death made it possible for Catherine to marry Thomas Seymour, 
but she died from complications of childbirth shortly after, in 
September 1548.
!TOPICS
HENRY VIII, SIX WIVES OF
