!TITLE
ONE OF THE MATH MONSTERS THE DAY HE WAS BORN
!WORDS
Charles Grandemange of France was essentially a human computer. He 
was born in 1835, a one pound baby, without legs or arms but endowed 
with a prodigious brain. He lived in a wooden box only one foot wide. 
He was one of those people called "Math monsters." 

He could multiply two 100-digit numbers by one another withn 30 
seconds. He could divide a 23-digit figure by another and find the 
remainder at one glance. He toured Europe at age 14 demonstrating his 
calculating ability. That's how he made money and supported himself. 
He was billed as the most lightning of all lightning fast 
calculators. 

Born into a poor family of seven children, he showed a special talent 
for mental arithmetic at a very young age. But "He is deprived of 
every kind of education, on the advice of certain personages who 
pretended that any work would destroy the native faculty of the child 
Day 1. However, he managed to train and read without a teacher as a 
teenager, and despite his disability, managed to write with the help 
of his dexter stump. 

"At my birth I was concealed from my mother by order of the doctors 
for a fortnight, and it was only after a preparation for the 
misfortune which befell her that I was at last placed under her care. 
When she started caring for me, I weighed less than a pound and a 
half. It is easy to understand that my childhood was surrounded by 
very dark omens. Born mutilated in this way, what future could I 
expect in this world? I was born into a working, honest, poor class. 
My father, a carpenter by trade, had great difficulty — even with 
what my mother, who was a weaver, could earn — to support four 
children. "

Strangely he married. His wife was essentially a caretaker. His 
marriage certificate includes his signature, which is of good graphic 
quality. He died in October, 1870 at 35 years of age.
!TOPICS
