!TITLE
BROKEN HEART SYNDROME
!WORDS
Broken-heart syndrome, also known as stress cardiomyopathy, is a 
heart condition that is often brought on by stressful situations and 
extreme emotions. It can also be triggered by a serious physical 
illness or surgery. The symptoms of this condition are sudden chest 
pain and shortness of breath12. The symptoms are so similar to those 
of a traditional heart attack that you, a paramedic, and even many ER 
doctors aren’t going to know the difference.

Broken-heart syndrome affects just part of the heart. It briefly 
interrupts the way the heart pumps blood. The rest of the heart 
continues to work as usual. Sometimes the heart contracts more 
forcefully. Medicines are used to treat symptoms of broken heart 
syndrome. The treatment consists of beta blockers, blood thinners, 
and diuretics
!TOPICS
BROKEN HEART SYNDROME
!BASE=FRS-4/9999
!SOURCE=3
!TCAID=0
!END


!TITLE
THE STRUGGLE OF CUBANS FOR FREEDOM
!WORDS
            At least 350,000 Cubans couldn't live with the Castro 
regime over 50 years ago, so they left and came to Miami. When they 
came out of Cuba, they couldn't bring anything with them. There was 
no money and no resources of any kind.  A few had some family here, 
but most were day workers with few resources themselves.

	Now those 350,000 Cubans constitute a major part of the population 
of the Miami area. They have proven to be so hard working, so 
determined to succeed, that the average income per family is well 
above the national average. More than half of them own their own 
homes, and they pump a monstrous total into the Miami economy every 
year. They have turned the area from a sleepy little, dull seasonal 
resort into a dynamic, year-around city. 

	They control much of all new construction there and have erected the 
largest office building in Miami. Many now serve as presidents and 
vice-presidents of banks. Cubans operate most of the restaurants, and 
the mayor of Miami said that the greatest thing that ever happened to 
Florida was the Cuban invasion. It all happened when people had their 
backs to the wall.
!TOPICS
