!TITLE
BURDENS BUILD CHARACTER
!WORDS
John Ruskin, a man of immense intelligence and a noted author, wrote 
in his old age about what he missed in his youth. He was the son of 
rich parents who gave him everything except, according to Ruskin, two 
things which every life needs. He puts it this way: (1) "I had 
nothing to love. My parents were remote and as planetary as the sun 
and moon. There was nobody to help, nobody to thank. (2) I had 
nothing to endure. Danger of any kind I knew not. My strength was 
never exercised, my patience never tried." Those are two great needs 
of life.

	On the other hand, let me tell you about Susanna and about how 
burdens build character. She was the twenty-fifth child in a 
dissenter’s family. A dissenter was an English Protestant who moved 
away in their thinking from the Church of England, we call the 
Episcopal Church.
             
           Though brilliant herself, Susanna attained little 
education. She married an older man and bore him nineteen children. 
Nine of them died early. Her house burned up twice. Her barn fell 
down. Her health failed, and she lived with the wolf at the door for 
the rest of her life. Her name was Susanna Wesley.

           Samuel and Susanna, married in 1689, and began pastoring 
in dreary little Epworth (England) in 1697. They served there forty 
years, enduring hardships like these:
         
           • Samuel’s salary was so small (and he was so incapable of 
managing it) that he was thrown into debtor’s prison twice, leaving 
Susanna to fend for herself.
           • They disagreed about Susanna’s ministry, for her Bible 
lessons drew more listeners than his sermons.
           • Susanna gave birth to a daughter in 1705. The nurse, 
exhausted by overnight carousing, slept so soundly the next morning 
that she rolled on the baby and smothered it.
          *Several of her children were so wayward that she called 
them “a constant affliction.”
           • Her brother promised her a sizable gift, which she 
looked forward to as the chance to start a new day of fiscal 
responsibility. He disappeared mysteriously and was never heard from 
again.
           • Finally, on July 21, 1731, Susanna described an accident 
in which her horses stampeded, throwing Samuel from their wagon and 
injuring him so badly that he was never well from that day on.
         
            A difficult life, wouldn’t you say? A lot of people would 
have just given up. And yet the parsonage at Epworth was destined to 
become the most celebrated one in English history, for from it came 
two of the greatest evangelists of all time, John and Charles Wesley. 

	John Wesley was the originator of the Methodist Church, and Charles 
Wesley was an unmatched creator of beautiful hymns. The number of his 
compositions greatly exceeds any other hymn-writer in the English 
language. To believers of every stripe throughout the Christian 
world, he is the Father of Sacred Song. Many of his hymns are in 
hymnbooks today. 

His biographer, says: "His name will live (forever) in the annals of 
the Church. He has no equal in the English language.” And the mother 
who raised them in every way fit the description of “weary and 
heavy-laden.” But she impacted the world because of her faith..
!TOPICS
HARDSHIPS
STRUGGLES
BURDENS BUILD CHARACTER
