!TITLE
WHERE HAVE ALL THE TEACHERS GONE?
!WORDS
Where Have All the Teachers Gone?
by Jade Bumgarner | Mar 4, 2024 |  
 
Most people become teachers because they want to make a difference in 
the lives of children. Teaching is a gift of the Spirit and not long 
ago, was a highly valued and admired profession. 
 
That is not what we see today. Teachers are leaving the profession at 
alarming rates, citing burnout, unrealistic expectations, negative 
impacts on their mental health and lack of support in meeting the 
emotional needs of children in the classroom. 
 
One survey found that “more than three-fourths (76.4%) of teachers 
considered leaving their position during the 2021-2022 school year.” 
And while the effects of online learning due to COVID-19 have 
impacted teacher burnout, many teachers continue to leave in droves 
even after the pandemic.
 
Many teachers leave because of pressure to show up for children in 
ways that are outside their expertise. I asked my neighbor, a 
4th-grade reading teacher, what the most significant challenge she 
faced as a teacher was. She responded, “The amount of responsibility 
being dumped on our shoulders is crippling and causes us to feel 
helpless. I am not a counselor, cop, psychologist, judge, 
pediatrician, pharmacist or jury. I am a reading teacher.” 
 
We wouldn’t show up to our doctor’s office looking for legal advice 
or walk into a hair salon seeking help for a car repair. Still, it 
seems widely assumed that teachers must go beyond their teaching 
capabilities to be considered successful educators. 
 
Without support or the presence of social workers, some teachers have 
experienced threats and attacks, both verbal and physical. Education 
cannot happen when there are constant behavioral interruptions and 
safety concerns. 
 
I asked my teacher-neighbor the impact these stressors have on 
teachers. She said, “I feel burned out, anxious and sad that the 
career that is my calling and spiritual gift feels like such a 
burden. My teammates have all been to multiple doctors this year: one 
with ulcers, one with a new anxiety diagnosis and one with an 
overload of stress-related cortisol, which causes facial swelling.”
!TOPICS
WHERE HAVE ALL THE TEACHERS GONE?
TEACHERS
PUBLIC EDUCATION
!BASE=FRS-4/9999
!SOURCE=3
!TCAID=0
!END


!TITLE
A 6 YR-OLD'S CONVERSATION WITH GREAT-GRANDDAD
!WORDS
In January, 2023 at Gigii's house (Angela Skaggs Lanye), we were 
celebrating a delayed Christmas with the Shane and Amy Jeffers family 
and the Robertson family (Sheena and Stephen and Arlo).

I was getting over an upper-respiratiory problem and while the the 
rest of the the family was outside playing some games, I stayed 
inside and watched what was going on. The kids--Arlo, Landon, 
Logan--were playing with the adults and having a great time.

Landon Jeffers (6 years old) came in to go to the bathroom and came 
by me. A very friendly (and smart) child, he stopped and said, "Why 
are you sitting in here?" I told him my reason and added, "There's a 
lot of wind out there, and I would rather stay out of it."

He said, "There's not much wind out there. It's not bad. You can come 
on out and watch us." I thanked him and said something like, "Well, I 
may be out there in a few minutes."  

He then asked, "Are you tired?" I assured him I wasn't and he said, 
"Well, come on out."

Then he said, "I hear you've got to leave early. Why?" I told him I 
had a funeral the next day and needed to get ready for it. I had some 
work to do.

He asked, "What kind of work do you do?"  (What kind of work?) I told 
him that I was a preacher (like he sees on Sunday morning). He said, 
"That shouldn't take long." Then he said, "If you bring your work 
over here, you won't have to leave so early?" I thanked him for his 
instruction.

FRS: I've never had a six-year-old use such precise language like 
that, carry on a conversation like that or ask such insightful 
questions as that. He does that a lot, at least in my presence. I 
jokingly say I don't talk to hm; he talks to me. And what a pleasure!
