!TITLE
DIVIDEND YIELD AS OPPOSED TO DIVIDENDS
!WORDS
The dividend yield is a financial ratio expressed as a percentage. It 
provides insight into how much a company pays out in dividends each 
year relative to its stock price. Here are the key points about 
dividend yield:

Calculation: The dividend yield is calculated by dividing the annual 
dividends per share by the price per share. Mathematically, it can be 
represented as: [ \text{Dividend Yield} = \frac{\text{Annual 
Dividends per Share}}{\text{Price per Share}} ]

Interpretation:

A higher dividend yield indicates that a company pays a larger 
portion of its profits as dividends.
Mature companies are more likely to pay dividends.

Sectors such as utilities and consumer staples often have relatively 
higher dividend yields.

Real estate investment trusts (REITs), master limited partnerships 
(MLPs), and business development companies (BDCs) tend to pay 
higher-than-average dividends, but these dividends are taxed at a 
higher rate.

Considerations:

Be cautious: A high dividend yield doesn’t always mean an attractive 
investment opportunity. Sometimes, a declining stock price can 
artificially inflate the yield.

Technology stocks typically have lower dividend yields.

Example: As of June 2023, Qualcomm Incorporated (QCOM), an 
established telecommunications equipment manufacturer, had a trailing 
twelve months (TTM) dividend of $3.20. With a current price of 
$140.20, its dividend yield was 2.30%. In contrast, Block, Inc. (SQ), 
a newer mobile payments processor, pays no dividends at all.
!TOPICS
DIVIDEND YIELD
INVESTING
WALL STREET
!BASE=FRS-4/9999
!SOURCE=3
!TCAID=0
!END


