!TITLE
THEY SAID HE WAS THE DIRTIEST MAN IN FOOTBALL
!WORDS

For an amazing 16 years, linebacker Bill Romanowski ruled the NFL 
gridiron with vicious tackles and cheap hits. Known as "Romo," he had 
a nasty reputation for rage and violence on the field. Driven by a 
fear of failure, he pushed his body to the limit, not only through 
weight-training, but with dietary supplements and illegal steroids.

"I compromised my morality to get ahead, to play another year, to 
play two more years, to win another Super Bowl," Romanowski said in a 
60 Minutes interview in 2005. But worse than the pain from all the 
vicious hits was "the embarrassment to my family, and friends and 
ultimately a little boy that looked up to his dad. And that one hurt 
me more than anything," Romanowski said.

But greater than the pain of the collisions and concussions was the 
pain of living without purpose and meaning. For Romo, unfortunately, 
football was not merely what he did, it was who he was.
!TOPICS
