!TITLE
DEACONESSES IN THE EARLY CHURCH
!WORDS
Deaconesses in the early church

Phoebe) she is called “a deacon (diakonon) of the
church at Cenchreae” (Romans 16: 1). The same Greek word for deacon 
that is used
for men in Timothy is the one used here for a deacon who is a female. 
It means “overseer”.

The NASV’s and NIV’s translation as “servant”
is inadequate. Phoebe was a deacon, the first deacon named in
Christian history! 

Origen, an early highly respected leader of the church, in his 
Commentary on the Epistle to the Romans, had this to say:

“This passage teaches that there were women ordained in the church’s
ministry by the apostles’ authority.”

Charles Talbert, Epistle to the Romans, Smith & Helwys


The evidence for a woman deacon (Phoebe, Rom 16:1-2), a
woman apostle (Junia, Rom 16:7), and various female laborers for
the Christian cause (Rom 16:7  is clear. 

Certain Christians are willing to grant the evidence even for a
woman deacon and a woman apostle but then offer qualifiers.
Thomas R. Schreiner is an example. About Phoebe, he has said:
The office of deacon, however, must be distinguished from that of
overseer/elder. . . . One should not conclude from Phoebe’s role as a
deacon that she functioned as a leader of the congregation. 
(This is a typical fundamentalist innterpretation of the Greek word 
"ddiakonon", which means "overseeers."


.
.
