!TITLE
NAZARETH IN THE FIRST CENTURY
!WORDS
In 2009, a first-century dwelling was discovered6 in which were found 
pottery and chalk stone vessel shards which date from the late 
Hellenic through Early Roman periods (100 BC to 100 AD)7

Another first-century courtyard house was excavated in Nazareth8, 
which still had windows and doors intact. In 2015 Dr. Ken Dark, the 
lead archaeologist, noted evidence of early Christian veneration at 
the site, suggesting that it may have been the childhood home of 
Jesus.

The rock-cut doorway of a first-century house discovered near the 
Sisters of Nazareth Convent, which may have been the childhood home 
of Jesus. .

While there once was a lack of first-century evidence in Nazareth, 
recent excavations have conclusively demonstrated that in Jesus’ day, 
Nazareth was a backwater village of around 50 houses about four acres 
in size and populated by devout Jews of modest means.10

In the historical biographies of Jesus in the Bible, Nazareth is 
identified as his hometown by each of the writers: Mathew (Mt 2:23), 
Mark (Mk 1:24), Luke (Lk 18:37), and John (Jn 19:19).  Some 30 years 
after Jesus’s death and resurrection, Christians were still known as 
the “sect of the Nazarenes.” (Acts 24:5).  These writers, along with 
the many people who spoke about “Jesus of Nazareth” were familiar 
with the village.  Upon hearing that Jesus of Nazareth was the 
Messiah, Nathaniel even asked, “Can anything good come out of 
Nazareth?” (Jn 1:46)

AUGUSTUS'S DECREE IN LUKE 2 DID NOT APPLY TO GALILEE. GALILEE WAS NOT 
UNDER ROMAN CONTROL,
