!TITLE
FRS-ATOKA CHURCH HISTORY
!WORDS
Brother Fred Skaggs was called by First Baptist Church in the fall of 
1963. Coming from 
Wardville Baptist Church, Wardville, Oklahoma. He, along with his 
wife, Jane and their five 
children, quickly won the hearts of FBC members. 

Sid and Kathryn Camp fondly reminisce of Brother Fred's encouragement 
in 1965 to become 
Falls Creek sponsors, greatly enlarged in his ministry, a position 
they served in for more than 20 years. To date, the Camps continue to 
be active in the care of our Falls Creek facility. 

Memories of gratitude are shared by Morris and Cindy Cochran, Jim and 
Sharon Cathey and 
Max and Judy Lane and many others for their lives and marriages have 
been enriched from the wisdom and guidance of his counseling. From 
these unions have come eight children, all members of FBC. Praise 
God! 

Jane Skaggs is described as a beautiful person both inside and out. 
Her years in Atoka were 
surely busy ones as a pastor's wife and mother while rearing five 
small children. She is remembered 
as an inspiration as she maintained her composure getting their five 
children to church -- even if 
her earrings were not a matching set! Her tactful, sweet spirit was a 
blessing to all. It should also 
be mentioned that her patience with Fred's love for horses and the 
stories that went with them have 
surely added jewels to her crown. 

For 26 years the outstanding memory of those who were privileged to 
study under Brother Fred's 
teaching have described him as a scholar, most intelligent and a 
wonderful, wonderful teacher of 
God's Word. 

Mrs. Olliebelle Thacker recorded in her Bible Bro. Fred's last 
service at FBC which was October 
2, 1966. The sermon subject for the morning service was "Finally My 
Brethren," taken from 
Ephesians 6:6-10. The evening sermon subject, "The Word In The Upper 
Room," followed by the 
Lord's Supper was, in Mrs. Thacker's memory, a beautiful service. 

The lasting effect of Fred Skagg's leadership upon First Baptist 
Church is evidence he was truly 
a man directed by God. Many sweet and beautiful memories were left by 
the Skaggs family for the 
history of our church for which we are so thankful. 

MRS. JEWEL CALHOUN
