!TITLE
THE SUNDAY SILENCE AND EASY GOER RIVALRY
!WORDS
The first was the epic battle between Affirmed and Alydar, the two 
rivals who had met six times during their juvenile campaigns on the 
East Coast in 1977, with Affirmed winning four of the six. 
Remarkably, in five of those six races, the pair finished 1-2.

Affirmed took the West  Coast route to the 1978 Triple Crown while 
Alydar stayed on the East Coast and in Kentucky, winning the Blue 
Grass Stakes in romping fashion by 13 lengths before going off as the 
favorite over Affirmed in the Kentucky Derby. But Affirmed got the 
jump on Alydar that day, winning comfortably with his rival getting 
up late for second. The Preakness was closer, Alydar charging to 
within a neck of Affirmed at the wire, but in the Belmont Stakes, 
Alydar hooked up with Affirmed much earlier in the race and those two 
battled on the front end for nearly a mile.

Alydar and jockey Jorge Velasquez were to the outside of Affirmed and 
Steve Cauthen, and in mid stretch Alydar poked his head in front of 
Affirmed. But, under left-handed urging from Cauthen, Affirmed 
regained the lead and beat his rival by a head to become horse 
racing’s third Triple Crown winner in six years. It would be 37 years 
before American Pharoah became the sport’s 12th Triple Crown winner.

After the Belmont Stakes, the score was Affirmed, 7 - Alydar 3.

In their final meeting in the mile and a quarter Travers Stakes at 
Saratoga. Affirmed controlled the pace, but as Alydar tried to move 
to his inside approaching the far turn, Laffit Pincay Jr. – subbing 
for an injured Cauthen – allowed Affirmed to drift to the inside, 
causing Alydar to take up sharply. Affirmed was first across the wire 
but stewards disqualified Affirmed and placed him second. That was 
their final meeting. In their 10 races together, they finished 1-2 
nine times. Now that was a rivalry.

Eleven years later, Sunday Silence and Easy Goer came to the 1989 
Triple Crown as the Best in the West and Best in the East, 
respectively. 

Trained by Shug McGaughey for Ogden Phipps, Easy Goer was a flashy 
chestnut who won seven of nine starts before the Kentucky Derby, 
often winning with ease. Many in the East Coast racing media were 
ready to anoint him the second coming of Secretariat.

Sunday Silence, a near-black, sickle-hocked colt who was pretty much 
disregarded as an ugly duckling in the sales ring, had won four of 
six races in California for veteran horseman Charlie Whittingham, 
including the Santa Anita Derby. He was co-owned by Whittingham, Dr. 
Ernest Gaillard and Arthur B. Hancock III, owner of Stone Farm where 
Sunday Silence was foaled and raised.

The human dynamics added to the rivalry.

Ogden Phipps was one of the trustees of Claiborne Farm who would have 
to decide which of the two Hancock brothers – Arthur or younger 
brother Seth – would replace their father in running the legendary 
Paris, Ky., nursery following the 1972 death of “Bull” Hancock. 
Phipps and the other trustees chose Seth, causing Arthur to leave 
Claiborne and go out on his own. For years, he was determined to make 
Stone Farm bigger than Claiborne, proving that he would have been a 
worthy successor to his father. 

Easy Goer was odds-on favorite in the Derby, but the racetrack was 
muddy that day, similar to the track on which he’d finished second in 
the previous year’s Breeders’ Cup Juvenile at Churchill Downs. That 
seemed like a legitimate excuse when he ran second, beaten 2 1/2 
lengths by Sunday Silence. The two colts came back two weeks later in 
the Preakness and put on one of the greatest shows ever seen at Old 
Hilltop, Patrick Valenzuela and Sunday Silence nosing out Pat Day and 
Easy Goer after a thrilling stretch run. This time there were no 
excuses for Easy Goer, who was losing to Sunday Silence as the 
odds-on favorite for the second time in a row.

When the Belmont Stakes arrived around three weeks later, Sunday 
Silence was finally installed as the favorite over Easy Goer, but 
this one was no match. Easy Goer ran away with the “test of the 
champion,” opening up a commanding lead at the top of the stretch and 
cruising to the wire eight lengths to the good of Sunday Silence.

The score was Sunday Silence, 2 - Easy Goer, 1. 

The horses took separate paths to the Breeders’ Cup Classic, held 
that year at Gulfstream Park, and despite Sunday Silence’s 2-1 edge, 
the memory of that Belmont romp by Easy Goer convinced fans to back 
the Alydar colt down to odds-on favoritism for the third time. And, 
for the third time, Sunday Silence turned back Easy Goer, this time 
to clinch Horse of the Year.


The two horses were to remain in training for their 4-year-old 
seasons, and there was even talk of a match race at Arlington Park in 
the summer of 1990, but Sunday Silence and Easy goer both sustained 
career-ending injuries before they could meet again.

Just like the fans who made Easy Goer favored over Sunday Silence in 
three of their four meetings, Kentucky breeders embraced the stallion 
prospects of Easy Goer, who retired to Claiborne Farm. Arthur Hancock 
couldn’t find more than two breeders’ willing to buy a share in 
Sunday Silence, so a deal was struck to sell the son of Halo to 
Japanese breeder Zenya Yoshida, who had become a minority owner in 
the colt before the Breeders’ Cup.

Sunday Silence stood at Yoshida’s Shadai Stallion Station and became 
the most successful sire in Japanese history, helping transform the 
country’s Thoroughbred industry from an international also-ran to a 
global powerhouse.



By Ray Paulick
