!TITLE
ATTITUDES ABOUT LIFE
!WORDS
"The man who views the world at 50 the same as he did at 20 has 
wasted 30 years of his life."
                        ----Muhammad Ali

Life isn't about waiting for the storm to pass. 
It's about learning to dance in the rain.


"It's hard to see a halo when you're looking for horns."          
Cullen Hightower

Some people spend their entire lives practicing being unhappy, 
diligently pursuing joylessness. They get more mileage from having 
people feel sorry for them than from choosing to live out their lives 
in the context of joy.

     FRS:  I was talking to a man whom I had never seen before about 
trimming some trees a few years ago. He gave me a price and then 
asked if I could pay him in cash. Well, of course, I knew exactly why 
he was asking that, but I pretended not to have any idea why he 
wouldn’t take my check. "Why?” I said. “My check is good,” I 
protested. He stuttered a minute and finally said, with a little 
smirk on his face, "Well, I know, but I try to keep this personal." I 
smiled, waited a minute and said, "Sir, I'm sorry to have to tell you 
this, but I work for the IRS." 
	
	Well, that fellow turned nine shades of green, two of red, then 
white. He was the whitest white man I’ve ever seen. He grabbed his 
face, smiled sheepishly and then said, "Oh, I was just kidding with 
you. I'm not into that kind of thing." Oh, yes he was! His intentions 
were perfectly clear, and no amount of disavowal was going to change 
that.



Dr. Benjamin Carson was a pioneer in the field of neurosurgery, the 
youngest chief of pediatric neurosurgery in the United States. He 
gained fame after leading a team of surgeons in the first known 
separation of conjoined twins joined at the back of the head. He 
performed the first successful neurosurgical procedure on a fetus 
inside the womb.  He retired as professor of neurosurgery, oncology, 
plastic surgery, and pediatrics at the Johns Hopkins School of 
Medicine. Dr. Carson tells a moving story about his mother. She 
insisted that Ben and his brother Curtis write a book report every 
couple of weeks. This wasn't for school—this was for their mom. 

	Ben and Curtis dutifully obeyed for years. 

	About the time he was in junior high, Ben learned something 
absolutely shocking. His mom couldn't read. For years Ben had read 
books and scratched out reports, assuming that his mom was checking 
every word, but she didn't have a clue what he was saying. 

	Now consider this: raised by an illiterate mother, Ben grew up to be 
a world-famous surgeon who was featured in many articles and was the 
author of several books. His illiterate mom didn't wring her hands 
over her lack of learning and give up hope of raising intelligent 
boys. Instead, she gave her boys what she had—encouragement, interest 
in learning, accountability, determination, the courage to demand 
extra work, and character. And it paid off in spades.
!TOPICS
ATTITUDES ABOUT LIFE
LIFE
PERSEPCTIVE ABOUT LIFE
ATTITUDE AND AGE
MOHAMMED ALI
PESSIMISM
DANCING IN THE RAIN
HAPPINESS
