!TITLE
A SPECIAL WORD TO LAURA JANE SKAGGS
!WORDS
My dear Laura,

Everybody in our family who is at all observant knows that I love my 
children, my grandchildren and my great-grandchildren without 
reservation. I have no favorites. Each one is special in their own 
way. I see that, and I celebrate that.

But there is something I want to say to you for you to hear while I’m 
still among the living. More than anybody else in our family, when it 
comes to children, you remind me so much of Grandma Jane. She had a 
way with children that was just hard to describe, as do you. Children 
don’t stand in line to do anything, but I and others have seen 
children, especially at Sunday School, stand in line to wait their 
turn to hug Miss Jane. There was just something in her that children 
loved.

I have observed you on several different occasions, and I see that in 
you. Just one example was my Father’s Day celebration yesterday. I 
watched as you interfaced with Abigail. You carry her around like 
some women do a large purse. She looks like she’s just part of you. 
If you had something to do, you did it, lugging her with you. You set 
her up on the table like a porcelain doll to write something. Then 
picked her up and headed out somewhere else. Abigail never made a 
sound. You’d speak to her, smile at her, and go on with what you were 
doing. It looked like you were her mother. What I’m trying to say is 
that this was a picture of a child at peace with what was happening 
with her and with the one who was making it happen. It was a 
beautiful picture, and it is a gift that in some ways is uniquely 
yours, at least as I see it.

April 6, 2006, I had a wedding between Kevin King and Tammy Williams. 
A week before the wedding, we were going over our final plans. I 
asked them if there was anything else they wanted to ask. Kevin said, 
“Yes. Is Miss Jane going to be there?” I was quite surprised. No one 
had ever asked me that before. I said, “Do you want her there?” He 
said, “Yes. if she could. I would really like that. She was so 
special to me.” Well, she came, but I’ve never forgotten that 
question and how she impacted so many lives.

I’m not trying to overplay this, but I see many of those same 
characteristics in you, and I just wanted to tell you. Thank you. You 
mean more to a lot of people than you probably think you do.

Love you,

Granddaddy
!TOPICS
LAURA JANE SKAGGS
FRED R. SKAGGS
APPRECIATION
!BASE=FRS-4/9999
!SOURCE=3
!TCAID=0
!END


!TITLE
THE DIVINE COUNCIL
!WORDS
DIVINE COUNCIL A term used by Hebrew Bible scholars for the heavenly 
host, the assembly of divine beings who administer the affairs of the 
cosmos under Yahweh, the God of Israel. All ancient Mediterranean 
cultures had some conception of a divine council, including Israel. 
However, Israelite religion’s divine council was distinct. The 
structure of the Israelite divine council has implications for 
understanding God and the unseen world in biblical theology.
Textual Evidence and its Ancient Canaanite Context

The Council of the Gods/God

Most Bible translations show that Israel believed in an assembly of 
heavenly host under the authority of Yahweh. Modern translations do 
not show clearly that this assembly is similar to pantheons of 
ancient Near Eastern cultures. A meeting of God and the heavenly 
hosts which points to God’s role as King of the universe. Some 
scholars have proposed an analogy with Mesopotamian and Canaanite 
myths about meetings of the pantheon of gods to decide the fate of 
the cosmos. For example, angels are depicted as presenting themselves 
before God, perhaps to report their contributions to His plan (Job 
1:6; 2:1) or to discuss how that plan will be effectuated (1 Kings 
22:20b; possibly Gen. 1:26, though this is doubtful). However, 
important differences exist. The monotheism of the Hebrew people is 
proclaimed, rather than called into question, by the council texts. 
Yahweh (the LORD) sits enthroned amidst the adoration and worship of 
the angelic creaturely beings (Ps. 29:1), and in the assembly He is 
greatly feared as well as praised (Ps. 89:5–8). His presiding over 
the assembly is directly tied to His sole claim as Ruler and Judge 
(Ps. 82:1, 8).

Humans are sometimes privy to the workings of God’s council. A true 
prophet of Yahweh is someone who has stood in God’s council. In his 
ordeal with the false prophets, Micaiah reports his observation of 
council deliberations (1 Kings 22:19–23). Likewise, Eliphaz asks Job 
if he stood in God’s council, implying that his claims would thereby 
be substantiated (Job 15:8). Jeremiah condemns those prophets who 
have not stood in God’s council, for if they had, they would know 
God’s plan and would not lead His people astray (Jer. 23:18, 22). 
Participation in the council by the prophet, then, leads to 
predictive success.
!TOPICS
THE DIVINE COUNCIL
!SCRIPTURES
JOB 1:6
JOB 2:1
1 KINGS 22:20
!BASE=FRS-4/9999
!SOURCE=3
!TCAID=0
!END


!TITLE
WORDS ABOUT "LIVING TIDAL"
!WORDS
IN just 8 days, my debut memoir opens up to the whole wide world 
(meaning if you don’t know me, and didn’t get a special advanced 
copy, your book will ship out June 25 from Amazon, Barnes & Noble or 
your local book store!) 

In celebration, I’m sharing 8 facts about writing this book! 

1. The note-taking and writing took 8 years! It took 3 years to live 
and then 5 years to write and re-write which really meant it took 5 
years for me to understand what I had lived enough to write about it. 

2. Distance from it all was required to be able to see the experience 
with new eyes. I finished the book while living in the Rocky 
Mountains: 11,000 feet above sea level where it all took place! 

3. Writing IS therapy. And my editors were so patient with me as 
chapters were added, removed and re-written every time I understood 
deeper, and a little more. 

4. I wanted to give up a million times. Voices of “This isn’t good 
enough;” “There are better, more interesting stories out there;” and 
“What you did wasn’t THAT special,” tried to stop many times.

5. I became pregnant three times and had two babies through the 
process of getting this book finished, which altered my identity 
completely. So, writing about a past version of myself was 
challenging in ways unexpected.

6. Writing about a past love while living within another type of love 
was also very challenging. It was like leaving and re-entering  
different worlds every time I sat down to write.

7. I learned so much from other authors and writing conferences. I’m 
thankful for those teachers. 

8. I learned so much from receiving rejections, “maybes,” and then, 
finally, a yes! (Lesson: Keep swimming through those shark-infested 
waters because you’ll find your right people!)

9. My husband demonstrated for me what support looks like: 
encouragement when I was feeling weak; helping me create time and 
space to write; reminding me that it’s not all “light a candle and 
find a quiet space” when writing—sometimes it’s just annoying work.

10. I learned to believe in ME—my voice, my talent, my perspective. 
Somewhere along the way, I stopped worrying if it was good enough and 
started saying, “This is so good!” 


You can get a signed copy here: 
https://www.sheenajeffers.com/buy/living-tidal
!TOPICS
LIVING TIDAL
SHEENA JEFFERS
