!TITLE
CAPT. JOHN SMITH AND ORAL TRADITION
!WORDS
Captain John Smith became the first English colonist to meet the 
paramount chief Powhatan. According to Smith's account, Pocahontas, 
Chief Powhatan's daughter, prevented her father from executing Smith.

Some researchers have asserted that a mock execution of Smith was a 
ritual intended to adopt Smith into the tribe, but other modern 
writers dispute this interpretation, noting that many of Smith's 
stories do not line up with the known facts. 

They point out that nothing is known of 17th-century Powhatan 
adoption ceremonies and that an execution ritual is different from 
known rites of passage. Other historians, such as Helen Rountree, 
have questioned whether there was any risk of execution. They note 
that Smith failed to mention it in his 1608 and 1612 accounts, and 
only added it to his 1624 memoir after Pocahontas had become famous.
!TOPICS
JOHN SMITH
POWHATAN
POCHONTAS
!BASE=FRS-4/9999
!SOURCE=3
!TCAID=0
!END


!TITLE
COMMENTS ON SOME EPHESIAN PASSAGES
!WORDS
Ephesians 3:1-13.  This passage is not one of my favorites about 
Paul.  He makes a claim in verse three that troubles me.  Here, and 
at other places in his writings, he declares that his ‘knowledge’ 
about Christian faith came to him by ‘personal revelation’ (only) 
(v.3).  Paul did not know Jesus personally, and he claims that he did 
not learn anything about the life and teachings of Jesus from any of 
the ‘eye-witnesses’ of Jesus’ life.  

I have not been able to find where Paul cited the teachings of Jesus 
as the basis for Paul’s teachings about the Christian life.  He 
declares that he was made an ‘apostle to the Gentiles’ by Jesus in 
his Damascus Road conversion experience, but in all his early 
preaching, he preached to Jews, and on his missionary journeys he 
went first to synagogues and worked among Jews until he was ‘driven’ 
to ‘turn to the Gentiles’ because he was  made to do so by rejection 
by Judaizers. 

Paul’s central tenet of faith is that the crucifixion of Jesus was a 
substitute blood sacrifice ‘to atone’ for  original sin so that 
humanity (Adam’s descendants) might be forgiven and no longer bear 
Adam’s guilt.  But his belief in substitute blood sacrifice came down 
to him in his childhood rearing in Gamaliel’s rabbinical school.

Substitute sacrifice was begun by Moses after the Exodus and made 
central in the animal sacrifices of Mosaic Law. Paul found in the 
crucifixion of Jesus a fulfillment of Mosaic atonement faith.  Now 
let me be  clear.  Paul was historically the most influential person 
in the development and spread of Christian faith during the first 
half-century after the life and death of Jesus.  Paul’s doctrine of 
salvation (and I believe it is different from that of Jesus) has 
predominated in the stream of Christian faith until the present.  
BUT, his writing about the Christian life, after conversion, ‘tracks’ 
well with the teaching and practice of Jesus.  I have high regard for 
Paul; I cannot imagine Christian history without him, but I wish he 
could have been a ‘bit more humble’ in his self-image, and  I have to 
wish he would have learned about the life and teachings of Jesus from 
those who ‘carried forward’ the traditions from which the four 
Gospels were written a generation later, after his martyrdom death.


Ephesians 4:8-10.  I need first to comment on the statement  that 
‘When he (Christ) ascended on high he led a host of captives’ (v.??.  
Paul cites Psalm 68:18 as his authority, but that passage is about 
God winning an earthly battle for Israel and coming from the battle 
leading the defeated army as captive slaves, which was a common way 
for ancient kings to demonstrate their victory in war.  Paul seems to 
be expressing a belief, like that of 1 Peter 3:19, that between 
crucifixion and resurrection Jesus went to sheol (the place of the 
dead) and ‘preached to the spirits in prison (people who had died 
before Jesus lived and died).  These were the ‘host of captives ‘ he 
led when he arose and ascended.’  This is an obscure tenet of faith 
that is found only in these two places in the Bible.  It is not 
supported by any other tenets of faith that I know about.  I can’t 
find help in word study.  The Greek text has two long words, 
different forms a complex word made from two roots meaning ‘to lead 
(or be led) by a spear.’  I am not  good enough linguist to tell if 
the grammatical forms of the words refer to the ‘condition’ 
(captivity, being captive) or to the persons (captives).  Both the 
KJV and my Greek interlinear say the victorious Christ led ‘captivity 
(the condition) captive’ meaning that Jesus had triumphed over the 
‘bondage of sin’ to liberate sinners by forgiveness.  Both RSV and 
NIV say that in the ascension, Christ led a ‘host of captives’ 
(persons whom he was liberating).  All of the transactions affirm 
that the ascending Christ did indeed bestow ‘gifts ‘ on humanity, 
which we will find and discuss in verses 11-16.   

Paul then does some interpreting himself.  He writes that you can’t  
talk about ‘ascending’  without considering ‘descending’ first.  Ok, 
but he doesn’t talk about Jesus ‘descending’ in incarnation, but 
‘descending into the lower parts of the earth’ (deeper than the 
grave,  into sheol, the place of the dead).  This would again seem to 
indicate that Paul did believe that the crucified Jesus went to sheol 
and preached, as 1 Peter 3:19 says.  That is a nuance of belief I do 
not believe, because I am persuaded that for Jesus at crucifixion and 
all people at physical death, the soul/spirit/person do not go into 
some ‘place of the dead, but they go on living  in the realm of 
spirit in the presence of God.  I believe the human spirit/soul is 
immortal, not subject to human death.

Sherrill Stevens 6/29/24
!TOPICS
EPHESIANS, COMMENTS ON
ATONEMENT
!SCRIPTURES
EPHESIANS 3:1-13
EPHESIANS 4:8-10
