!TITLE
TYPES OF INTELLIGENCE
!WORDS
                                                                   
Types of Intelligence

Certainly! Fluid intelligence refers to the ability to reason and 
think flexibly, especially in novel situations where you don’t rely 
on prior knowledge. It involves abstract thinking, problem-solving, 
and adapting to new challenges. For instance, when faced with a 
completely unfamiliar problem, you draw upon fluid intelligence to 
find a solution. As we age, fluid intelligence tends to decline after 
adolescence.

On the other hand, crystallized intelligence is based on knowledge 
acquired through education and experience. It includes facts, 
vocabulary, and skills accumulated over time. Examples of 
crystallized intelligence include memorizing text, recalling how to 
perform specific tasks, and remembering historical dates. 
Interestingly, crystallized intelligence tends to increase with age 
as we accumulate more learning and experience

•	Fluid intelligence: Current ability, openness to learning, 
decreases with age.
•	
•	Crystallized intelligence: Prior learning, recalling specific 
facts, increases with age.
!TOPICS
INTELLIGENCE
TYPES OF INTELLIGENCE
AGING
