!TITLE
MYTHS COMMONLY TOLD
!WORDS
Myth: People Were Burned at the Stake During the Salem Witch Trials
Though 20 different people were indeed convicted of witchcraft during 
the infamous Salem hearings of 1692 to 1693, none of them were burned 
at the stake. Nineteen of them — 14 women and five men — were hanged, 
five died in jail, and one man was pressed to death with stones after 
refusing to enter a plea. The confusion stems from the fact that 
those found guilty of witchcraft in Europe (where it was treated as 
heresy) were burned at the stake. “Burning was supposedly a way to 
purify the convict, and also as a threat to uncover conspiracies,” 
according to The Salem Witchcraft Trials: A Legal History author 
Peter Hoffer. Hanging them, meanwhile, was punitive.

Myth: Marie Antoinette Said “Let Them Eat Cake”
It’s gone down in history as one of the most out-of-touch quotes of 
all time — one that emblematized the last queen of France’s disregard 
for her own people. There’s just one problem: Marie Antoinette never 
said it. The actual words in question, “qu’ils mangent de la 
brioche,” come from Jean-Jacques Rousseau’s autobiographical book 
Confessions, in which he wrote: “At length I remembered the last 
resort of a great princess who, when told that the peasants had no 
bread, replied: ‘Then let them eat brioches.’”That passage was 
written in 1765, at which time Marie Antoinette was still a child and 
had yet to step foot in the country she helped rule from 1774 until 
the French monarchy was abolished in 1792, a year before her 
execution. After accidentally stepping on the executioner’s foot, she 
spoke her last words, which were considerably more polite than the 
quote so often attributed to her: “Pardon me, sir, I did not do it on 
purpose.”

Myth: Napoleon Was Short
Despite having a certain complex named after him, Napoleon Bonaparte 
was of average height for his time. Part of the confusion stems from 
the nickname “Le Petit Caporal,” which makes him sound “little” but 
was actually a term of endearment among his troops. There’s also the 
fact that inches were measured differently in 19th-century France 
than they are today. The former was equivalent to 2.71 centimeters, 
whereas the current measurement is 2.35 centimeters, which explains 
why he was only considered 5 feet, 2 inches tall when he died. Most 
estimates put him closer to 5 feet, 6 inches or 5 feet, 7 inches — 
not exactly a towering figure, but average or slightly above average 
by 18th-century standards.

Myth: Albert Einstein Failed Math
Though it’s often cited as evidence of his humble beginnings, 
Einstein didn’t actually fail math. “I never failed in mathematics,” 
Einstein said in 1935 when presented with a Ripley's Believe It or 
Not! headline claiming he had. “Before I was 15 I had mastered 
differential and integral calculus.” The anecdote is often retold to 
inspire the rest of us not to let early setbacks deter us from 
chasing our dreams and reaching our full potential — a worthy 
sentiment to be sure, just not one supported by the evidence in this 
case.
!TOPICS
MYTHS COMMONLHY TOLD
ORAL TRADITION
SALEM WITCH TRIALS
MARIE ANTOINETTE
NAPOLEON
ALBERT EINSTEIN
